******
[4] Turkey's neighbors - apprehension
Date: Mon 23 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: PanARMENIAN.Net, 17 Jan 2006 [edited]
<http://panarmenian.net/news/eng/?nid=16031&folder=2&attr=13>

FAO: Bird Flu May Have Already Penetrated into Armenia, Iran and Syria
-----------------------------------------------
[On 16 Jan 2006], the UN Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) stated
that "there are no reasons for not believing the avian influenza virus has
not crossed the eastern limits of Turkey." Organization specialist Dr. Juan
Labroth, who recently returned from Turkey, said the only confirmed case of
infection with H5N1 virus in Turkey that had led to death was registered in
Arlik village, bordering Armenia. Having confirmed the FAO statement that
it has not been ruled out that the bird flu virus has penetrated into
countries adjacent to Turkey -- Armenia, Iran, Syria -- Labroth stated that
"the FAO has to get reliable and transparent information from countries
neighboring Turkey, which will ensure [the] absence of avian influenza in
those countries."
Answering the question of whether Armenia has gotten in touch with the FAO
about the bird flu issue, the UN specialist said, "Armenia kept in touch
with the organization within the framework of other programs; however, no
specific report on the state of [the] health of birds was received from the
Armenian Government."
"Within [the] past few months, we [have] received reports [of a] high level
of bird death[s] in countries neighboring with Turkey, owing to poisoning
or other diseases. However, the diagnoses are to be confirmed by FAO
laboratories and the World Organization for Animal Health," Lubroth said.
Cases of bird deaths are registered in a number of Armenian villages. Local
authorities and high ranking officials of the staff for fighting bird flu
assure the public that the dead birds were examined in laboratories and
bird flu was not found.
"Words are not enough. It should be proved," Lubroth stated. "We would like
to closely cooperate with Armenian authorities [and] help them make sure
the virus is absent," the UN specialist remarked. The FAO will send its
specialists to Armenia, Georgia and Ukraine to check on whether their
laboratories are able to provide accurate diagnostics, he said.
--
